definition.value: A person who is a student in higher education, i.e. in undergraduate or postgraduate education.
A person who is a student in continuing education, i.e. in vocational education.
A student in an undergraduate program.
A student in an postgraduate program.
A student in a college.
A student in a university.
College students who are LGBTQIA+.
A college student who is bisexual.
A mood state which is considered "normal", usually non-depressive and non-manic in nature; may sometimes be considered to be positive.

A normal, non-depressed, and (typically) reasonably positive mood. Also used to describe a stable mental state or mood in those affected with bipolar disorder that is neither manic nor depressive, yet is distinguishable from healthy controls.
The gaze of the male viewer toward a male subject.
The gaze of the female viewer toward a female subject.
A notional environment in which communication over computer networks occurs.
The physical world or reality, as opposed to cyberspace or virtual reality.
An assistive device used to aid in ambulation.

A chair with wheels, used when walking is difficult or impossible due to illness, injury, old age related problems, or disability. These can include spinal cord injuries (paraplegia, hemiplegia, and quadriplegia), broken leg(s), cerebral palsy, brain injury, osteogenesis imperfecta, motor neurone disease (MND), multiple sclerosis (MS), muscular dystrophy (MD), spina bifida, among other conditions.
Chairs mounted on wheels and designed to be propelled by the occupant.
A wheelchair that is propelled by means of an electric motor (usually using differential steering) rather than manual power.
Any of various types of chairs used primarily for assistive purposes.
A piece of furniture made for an individual to sit upon.
Any of various organizations created by law or public authority.
An organization in which individuals are housed or live.
An institution where persons are confined for punishment under the guise of public protection.
A typically long-term holding facility usually used for those serving longer sentences. Prisons are usually federal or state facilities.
A short-term holding facility usually used for the newly arrested or those waiting trial or sentencing. Jails are usually local facilities.

A place where people are imprisoned by a third party that is contracted by a government agency. Private prison companies typically enter into contractual agreements with governments that commit prisoners and then pay a per diem or monthly rate, either for each prisoner in the facility, or for each place available, whether occupied or not. Such contracts may be for the operation only of a facility, or for design, construction and operation.

A penal institution in which a large number of individuals, typically those belonging to specific ethnic or racial categories (or other categories which a government has deemed dangerous or undiserable), are held without charges or intent to file charges. Oftentimes the term is applied to such confinement during warfare and often includes political prisoners.
A concentration camp in which the primary purpose of the camp is to kill those within it.
A site for the containment of enemy combatants captured by a belligerent power in time of war.
A weapon, typically a firearm, which is concealed from view.
The practice of carrying a weapon in public in a concealed or hidden manner, either on one's person or in close proximity.
The practice of carrying a firearm in public in a concealed or hidden manner, either on one's person or in close proximity.
A person who has been confined to an institution, such as a prison or hospital.

label.value: person who has been convicted of a crime

definition.value: A person who has been convicted of a crime or crimes.
LGBTQ people who are prisoners.
A transgender person who is a prisoner.
A person who has been convicted of a felony.

label.value: person who has committed a felony

definition.value: A person who is guilty of having committed a felony.

label.value: person who has committed a property crime

definition.value: A person who is guilty of a property crime.
A person who is guilty of theft.
A person who is guilty of burglary.
A person who is guilty of robbery.
A criminal behavior involving property.
The taking of another person's property or services without that person's permission or consent with the intent to deprive the rightful owner of it.
Illegally entering a building or other areas to commit a crime. Usually that offense is theft, but most jurisdictions include others within the ambit of burglary.

The crime of taking or attempting to take anything of value by force, threat of force, or by putting the victim in fear. According to common law, robbery is defined as taking the property of another, with the intent to permanently deprive the person of that property, by means of force or fear; that is, it is a larceny or theft accomplished by an assault.
A person who was convicted of a crime and then was later officially declared innocent of that same crime.
A person who has been convicted of a crime which they did not commit.

label.value: person previously convicted of a crime

definition.value: A person who had previously been convicted of a crime; i.e. an individual who has been convicted of a crime, but has been released from or has otherwise been deemed to have served an appropriate sentence related to that crime.
Traditionally, a criminal behavior of high seriousness, whereas a misdemeanor is regarded as less serious.

In the United States, where the felony/misdemeanor distinction is still widely applied, the federal government defines a felony as a crime punishable by death or imprisonment in excess of one year. If punishable by exactly one year or less, it is classified as a misdemeanor. The classification is based upon a crime's potential sentence, so a crime remains classified as a felony even if a defendant receives a sentence of less than a year of incarceration. Individual states may classify crimes by other factors, such as seriousness or context.
A statement or declaration which is an authentication of a fact or an attestation as to the truth of a matter.
